:: LCx {"position":"2375,3050","size":"100,100"}
The Left Circumflex Artery supplies the lateral portion of the heart. 
This would be reflected in leads I, aVL, V5, & V6

{<div  style="overflow:scroll">
<img
src=https://lanea5.github.io/Resday3/page01.jpg
width="700" height="900"
</div>}

Notice how on the image below, precordial leads V5, & V6 are placed anatomically diectly over the vessles descending from the LCx. Leads AVL and I use geometric calculations to find the mean electrical vector to between points on the EKG.
The image below stresses the important of accurate lead placement when preforming EKG

{<div  style="overflow:scroll">
<img
src=https://ecgwaves.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/ecg-localization-myocardial-infarction-stemi-ischemia-coronary-artery-occlusion.jpg
width="700" height="500"
</div>}


---

Take a look at the images above and infer which vessle supplies leads [[V2&V3]]


