:: Patient EKG interprered as Inferior MI {"position":"2525,2175","size":"100,100"}
''Your patients EKG (text-style:"underline")[did not ] have the characteristics of an inferior MI''

Characteristics of an inferior MI include :

* ST-segment elevation and T wave inversion in (text-style:"bold","underline")[at least 2 two contiguous leads]
	* Contiguous leads for inferior MI's are leads II, III, and aVF
* Reciprocal changes in leads I, aVL, and possibly V4
* Left electrical axis deviation
ST Elevation is defined as a deviation from the isoeletric line by +0.1 millivolt (1mm) . This deviatrion is measured at the J-point




(align:"=><=")+(box:"X=")[(text-style:"bold","underline")[Measuring J-Point] {<div>
<img
src=https://lanea5.github.io/Resday3/jpoint.PNG
width="400" height="300"
</div>}]

(align:"=><=")+(box:"X=")[(text-style:"bold","underline")[
''J-Point Elevation''] {<div>
<img
src=https://lanea5.github.io/Resday3/jpe.PNG
width="400" height="300"
</div>}]

Typically you will see ST-segment/ J-point elevation in the area of the heart that is being affected by the ischemic changes and you will see reciprocal changes (usually ST-segment/j-point depression) in the ekg lead(s) that are opposite that area of the heart. 
EKG leads that "show" the same areas of the heart are refered to as "contiguous leads". 
Areas that show reciprical chages are typically anatomically opposite of each other
For example:
* Anterior leads (V2-3) are reciprocal to posterior leads (V7, V8, V9). 
* Lateral leads (I and aVL) are reciprocal to Inferior leads (II, III and aVF)

Below is a list of more contiguous leads. 

{<div style="overflow:scroll">
<img
src=https://lanea5.github.io/Resday3/page01.jpg
width="700" height="900"
</div>}

---
It is important to note the difference between precordial leads (V1,V2,V3,V4,V5 and V6) from augmented limb leads (aVR, aVL and aVF), and limb leads (I, II and III). An Inferior MI will have changes in the limb/augmented limb leads, but will not have changes in the precordial leads (unless there is a secondary ischemic change). 

Below is an example of an inferior MI 

{<div  style="overflow:scroll">
<img
src=https://www.healio.com/~/media/learningsites/learntheheart/assets/4/a/8/b/inferiorstemi_blog4.webp
width="700" height="200"
</div>}

---
An important note for Inferior MI's is that Nitro should be used (text-style:"bold","underline")[with extreme caution] in patients with this pathology. 
Inferior MI's often have an element of Right Ventricular Wall involvement and the adminstration of Nitro for this population may rapidly decrease the patients blood pressure. 
This is because these MI's are "preload dependent". An injury to the right ventricular wall can result in decreased contractility in the rt side of the heart, this on its own may result in a low blood pressure for the patient. When Nitro is added to this pathology,the patients preload is lowered and their blood pressure may become dangeriously low.  



---
Let's go back to the [[room]] and look at your patients EKG again


:: Patient EKG interprered as Inferior MI {"position":"2525,2175","size":"100,100"}
''Your patients EKG (text-style:"underline")[did not ] have the characteristics of an inferior MI''

Characteristics of an inferior MI include :

* ST-segment elevation and T wave inversion in (text-style:"bold","underline")[at least 2 two contiguous leads]
	* Contiguous leads for inferior MI's are leads II, III, and aVF
* Reciprocal changes in leads I, aVL, and possibly V4
* Left electrical axis deviation
ST Elevation is defined as a deviation from the isoeletric line by +0.1 millivolt (1mm) . This deviatrion is measured at the J-point




(align:"=><=")+(box:"X=")[(text-style:"bold","underline")[Measuring J-Point] {<div>
<img
src=https://lanea5.github.io/Resday3/jpoint.PNG
width="400" height="300"
</div>}]

(align:"=><=")+(box:"X=")[(text-style:"bold","underline")[
''J-Point Elevation''] {<div>
<img
src=https://lanea5.github.io/Resday3/jpe.PNG
width="400" height="300"
</div>}]

Typically you will see ST-segment/ J-point elevation in the area of the heart that is being affected by the ischemic changes and you will see reciprocal changes (usually ST-segment/j-point depression) in the ekg lead(s) that are opposite that area of the heart. 
EKG leads that "show" the same areas of the heart are refered to as "contiguous leads". 
Areas that show reciprical chages are typically anatomically opposite of each other
For example:
* Anterior leads (V2-3) are reciprocal to posterior leads (V7, V8, V9). 
* Lateral leads (I and aVL) are reciprocal to Inferior leads (II, III and aVF)

Below is a list of more contiguous leads. 

{<div style="overflow:scroll">
<img
src=https://lanea5.github.io/Resday3/page01.jpg
width="700" height="900"
</div>}

---
It is important to note the difference between precordial leads (V1,V2,V3,V4,V5 and V6) from augmented limb leads (aVR, aVL and aVF), and limb leads (I, II and III). An Inferior MI will have changes in the limb/augmented limb leads, but will not have changes in the precordial leads (unless there is a secondary ischemic change). 

Below is an example of an inferior MI 

{<div  style="overflow:scroll">
<img
src=https://www.healio.com/~/media/learningsites/learntheheart/assets/4/a/8/b/inferiorstemi_blog4.webp
width="700" height="200"
</div>}

