:: Patient presented with New LBBB + Chest Pain {"position":"2525,2300","size":"100,100"}
''Your patients EKG (text-style:"underline")[did not ] have the characteristics of a LBBB''

Characteristics of a Left Bundle Branch Block (LBBB) include :

* QRS complex greater than 0.12 second
* Widened S wave in lead V1
* Positive T wave in lead V1
* Initial positive deflection in lead V6 (tall, notched R wave)--This is often refered to as "bunny ears" on V6; this characteristic is often seen on V5 as well. 

If acute, a LBBB may indicate acute myocardial infarction and is one of the indications for thrombolysis or transfer for PCI

Below is an example of a LBBB EKG 
Note the prominent "Bunny Ears" on lead V5 

{<div 
 style="overflow:scroll" class="image-container">
<img
src=https://www.skillstat.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/12-Lead-ECG-Practice-Quiz-Question-3-white.png
width="1050" height="450"
<div class="overlay-text"
</div>}
